stylometry: Bayes' theory allows us to change the probabilities when new information becomes available - turning the previous probabilities into what we call the posterior probabilities. It is important because new information can always be a changing factor and this rule let's us make adjustments in our probability factors. The posterior probabilities are determined by the offset in the new information - there is also an equation that can be used to determine the posterior probabilities. Posterior probabilites are important, we need them because that information is still there and available, just because the new information changes one factor, we still need the factors that were originally used - therefore this let's us still have those particular probabilities.
